# Policy Conventions

## Why Pundit

DHH would keep authorization in model methods and controller `before_action` guards. Pundit earns its dependency: one policy per model, one method per action, one place to look. Every controller action calls `authorize`. Every index calls `policy_scope`. Default posture: `after_action :verify_authorized` (and `verify_policy_scoped` on index) so a missed `authorize` or `policy_scope` raises during the request (in all environments, unless you customize Pundit or disable those callbacks). For actions that intentionally have no authorization (public pages, health checks), use `skip_after_action` explicitly — see the policies skill § Skipping Verification.

Policies answer **authorization** (“who may do this?”), not business rules (“what happens when they do?”). Domain logic stays on the model; policies compose model predicates.

> **Dependency note:** Pundit is a thin library (~300 lines) that provides a convention, not a framework. It adds `authorize` and `policy_scope` to controllers and maps them to plain Ruby objects. There is no DSL, no configuration, no runtime magic. It stays out of your way.

## One Policy Per Model

Every model exposed through a controller gets a policy in `app/policies/`. The policy mirrors the controller's CRUD actions.

```ruby
# app/policies/article_policy.rb
class ArticlePolicy < ApplicationPolicy
  def index?
    true
  end

  def show?
    true
  end

  def create?
    user.present?
  end

  def update?
    owner_or_admin?
  end

  def destroy?
    owner_or_admin?
  end

  private
    def owner_or_admin?
      record.creator == user || user.admin?
    end
end
```

## ApplicationPolicy as Base

Define sensible defaults — deny everything, then open up per-policy:

```ruby
# app/policies/application_policy.rb
class ApplicationPolicy
  attr_reader :user, :record

  def initialize(user, record)
    @user = user
    @record = record
  end

  def index?   = false
  def show?    = false
  def create?  = false
  def new?     = create?
  def update?  = false
  def edit?    = update?
  def destroy? = false

  class Scope
    attr_reader :user, :scope

    def initialize(user, scope)
      @user = user
      @scope = scope
    end

    def resolve
      raise NotImplementedError, "#{self.class} must implement #resolve"
    end

    private :user, :scope
  end
end
```

## Controller Integration

Call `authorize` in every action. Pundit raises `Pundit::NotAuthorizedError` on denial — handle it once in `ApplicationController`:

```ruby
class ArticlesController < ApplicationController
  def show
    @article = Article.find(params[:id])
    authorize @article
  end

  def create
    @article = Article.new(article_params)
    authorize @article

    if @article.save
      redirect_to @article
    else
      render :new, status: :unprocessable_content
    end
  end
end
```

## Scoping Collections

Use `policy_scope` in index actions to filter records, then authorize `index?` — typically with the model class (matches common Pundit usage). Assign the scoped relation to an instance variable for the view; you can pass the scoped relation to `authorize` instead if `index?` needs it.

```ruby
def index
  @articles = policy_scope(Article).chronologically
  authorize Article
end
```

Alternatively: `authorize @articles` — Pundit passes the relation as `record` to `index?`. Pick one style and stay consistent.

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Instead |
|-------------|---------|
| Authorization *policy* checks in controller `before_action` | `authorize @record` in the action body — use `before_action` for authentication (`authenticate_user!`, session), not for Pundit |
| Mirroring the full permission matrix on the model (`editable_by?` everywhere) | Policy methods (`update?`); keep domain predicates on the model (`published?`, `owned_by?(user)`) and call them from policies |
| Checking `current_user.admin?` inline in actions | Policy method encapsulates the check |
| Giant case/switch in a single permission method | One policy method per CRUD action |
| Custom verb methods (`close?`, `publish?`) | CRUD only — state changes map to `create?`/`destroy?` on a noun-resource policy |
| Skipping authorize for any action (including index) | `after_action :verify_authorized` — use `skip_after_action` only when an action intentionally has no authorization |
| Skipping `policy_scope` on index when the listing is user-specific | `policy_scope` in index; consider `after_action :verify_policy_scoped, only: :index` in `ApplicationController` |
| Policy reaching into `request` or `params` | Policies only see `user` and `record` |
| Business logic in policies | Policies answer "can this user do this?" — nothing else |
